WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.195 --> 00:00:01.868
(audience laughing)
- All right.

00:00:01.868 --> 00:00:03.278
So very exciting.

00:00:03.278 --> 00:00:05.109
We're here at Khan Academy with the team

00:00:05.109 --> 00:00:08.109
and we have some students
from Khan Lab School as well

00:00:08.109 --> 00:00:12.341
with the, I'd say legendary
Francis Ford Coppola,

00:00:12.341 --> 00:00:14.508
most known for filmmaking.

00:00:15.673 --> 00:00:19.594
Obviously The Godfather
movies, Apocalypse Now, Patton.

00:00:19.594 --> 00:00:20.552
I think by the time you were in--

00:00:20.552 --> 00:00:21.723
- The Outsiders.

00:00:21.723 --> 00:00:23.473
- The Outsiders, yes.

00:00:24.511 --> 00:00:27.707
You have more Academy
Awards than most of us,

00:00:27.707 --> 00:00:29.928
(audience laughs)

00:00:29.928 --> 00:00:31.617
but not just, I mean,
I think the one thing

00:00:31.617 --> 00:00:33.983
that we're all gonna learn today is

00:00:33.983 --> 00:00:36.190
as much as Francis is a legend

00:00:36.190 --> 00:00:38.865
and knows so much and
is so steeped in film

00:00:38.865 --> 00:00:41.187
that his interests go well beyond film.

00:00:41.187 --> 00:00:44.187
Obviously wine now and other things.

00:00:45.421 --> 00:00:49.375
Maybe a good place to
start since you are known

00:00:49.375 --> 00:00:51.604
so much as a legendary filmmaker

00:00:51.604 --> 00:00:53.100
is how did you get into that?

00:00:53.100 --> 00:00:55.723
What was your arc from maybe being

00:00:55.723 --> 00:00:57.653
the age of some of these
students at Khan Lab School,

00:00:57.653 --> 00:00:59.167
you know, in your middle school

00:00:59.167 --> 00:01:01.516
to eventually becoming a filmmaker?

00:01:01.516 --> 00:01:03.757
- Well, for some reason my father,

00:01:03.757 --> 00:01:06.746
who was a classical musician,

00:01:06.746 --> 00:01:09.192
moved every eight months it seemed

00:01:09.192 --> 00:01:12.730
and we were always in a new
house, in a new neighborhood,

00:01:12.730 --> 00:01:15.892
and I was always the new kid at school

00:01:15.892 --> 00:01:18.656
and my name was Francis, so they was,

00:01:18.656 --> 00:01:20.755
"Oh, that's a girl's name."

00:01:20.755 --> 00:01:24.924
So I got all of the typical
hazing when you're the new kid,

00:01:24.924 --> 00:01:27.378
but I was very good at science.

00:01:27.378 --> 00:01:29.932
I was very interested in
science and electricity

00:01:29.932 --> 00:01:34.454
and I used to love to read
the lives of the inventors

00:01:34.454 --> 00:01:36.840
and I felt I knew all about that,

00:01:36.840 --> 00:01:39.794
so much to this extent that
when my father asked me

00:01:39.794 --> 00:01:42.313
what I wanted to be when I grew up,

00:01:42.313 --> 00:01:44.241
I said, "A nuclear physicist."

00:01:44.241 --> 00:01:46.685
And he said to me, "Francis,
you can't flunk algebra

00:01:46.685 --> 00:01:49.748
"three times in a row and
be a nuclear physicist."

00:01:49.748 --> 00:01:51.307
And I said, "Why not?"

00:01:51.307 --> 00:01:53.946
But nonetheless, I was discouraged

00:01:53.946 --> 00:01:56.448
that I could ever be a scientist,

00:01:56.448 --> 00:01:57.599
which is what I wanted to be,

00:01:57.599 --> 00:01:59.891
because I was not good at math.

00:01:59.891 --> 00:02:01.629
So whenever I went to a new school--

00:02:01.629 --> 00:02:03.172
- But you were very strong at geometry.

00:02:03.172 --> 00:02:05.520
- I was very, I won the geometry medal.

00:02:05.520 --> 00:02:06.941
- [Interviewer] Yes, so it's that.

00:02:06.941 --> 00:02:09.369
- I was really good at geometry,
but geometry you can see

00:02:09.369 --> 00:02:13.362
and you can see the whole all the time.

00:02:13.362 --> 00:02:16.313
Sometimes it's not
clear, but you see it all

00:02:16.313 --> 00:02:18.966
and I was good at that.

00:02:18.966 --> 00:02:21.598
So whenever I went to a new school,

00:02:21.598 --> 00:02:23.875
I would always head to
the theater department

00:02:23.875 --> 00:02:25.396
because they always needed people

00:02:25.396 --> 00:02:29.126
who were good with
electricity and technology

00:02:29.126 --> 00:02:30.841
and also that's where the girls were.

00:02:30.841 --> 00:02:31.897
(audience laughs)

00:02:31.897 --> 00:02:33.259
And I wanted to meet them.

00:02:33.259 --> 00:02:34.815
(audience laughs)

00:02:34.815 --> 00:02:38.442
So I figured if I was around
the theater department working,

00:02:38.442 --> 00:02:40.422
I would get to meet the girls.

00:02:40.422 --> 00:02:42.539
I could've also gone to the football team

00:02:42.539 --> 00:02:45.228
where they had girls, but
I didn't qualify for that.

00:02:45.228 --> 00:02:47.098
(audience laughs)

00:02:47.098 --> 00:02:49.704
An interesting note to understand me

00:02:49.704 --> 00:02:51.213
is that when I was nine years old,

00:02:51.213 --> 00:02:53.567
I was paralyzed with polio,

00:02:53.567 --> 00:02:56.234
which was a big epidemic in 1949

00:02:57.195 --> 00:03:01.362
and it struck kids, many many
many children were paralyzed

00:03:02.341 --> 00:03:07.157
until only a few years
later I think, 1951, '52,

00:03:07.157 --> 00:03:11.074
they developed a vaccine
and the Sabin vaccine,

00:03:12.105 --> 00:03:16.180
but my generation, polio was
the scary children's disease

00:03:16.180 --> 00:03:19.284
and I got it and I missed the sixth grade

00:03:19.284 --> 00:03:21.530
because I couldn't walk,

00:03:21.530 --> 00:03:26.099
but through the wonderful
hospices of the March of Dimes,

00:03:26.099 --> 00:03:28.729
it was a charity called
the March of Dimes.

00:03:28.729 --> 00:03:32.896
Everyone donated dimes to
it and they sent a therapist

00:03:34.244 --> 00:03:36.962
who slowly brought me back to the ability

00:03:36.962 --> 00:03:39.278
to walk about a year and a half later.

00:03:39.278 --> 00:03:42.390
- Wow, and so how did you go from

00:03:42.390 --> 00:03:43.408
that state you're talking about

00:03:43.408 --> 00:03:46.584
where you were a little bit
involved with drama and theater

00:03:46.584 --> 00:03:49.588
to actually deciding that
you wanted to be a filmmaker

00:03:49.588 --> 00:03:51.379
and actually making films?

00:03:51.379 --> 00:03:53.637
- Well, I had an older
brother, five years older,

00:03:53.637 --> 00:03:56.379
who was a very good
student and very handsome

00:03:56.379 --> 00:04:00.394
and very accomplished and
wonderful to me by the way

00:04:00.394 --> 00:04:03.371
and I just wanted to be like him.

00:04:03.371 --> 00:04:07.308
In fact, he was already
interested in writing stories

00:04:07.308 --> 00:04:10.276
and his name was August Floyd Coppola

00:04:10.276 --> 00:04:14.731
and I just thought that was so
cool that I made my own name,

00:04:14.731 --> 00:04:17.478
Francis Ford Coppola, just to imitate him.

00:04:17.478 --> 00:04:19.123
(audience chuckles)

00:04:19.123 --> 00:04:20.971
- [Interviewer] Ford, it
was not part of your name?

00:04:20.971 --> 00:04:23.298
- Ford is my middle name, but I used it

00:04:23.298 --> 00:04:26.455
because my brother had,
but I was born in Detroit

00:04:26.455 --> 00:04:29.140
and my middle name was after Henry Ford

00:04:29.140 --> 00:04:32.340
'cause my father, who
was a classical musician

00:04:32.340 --> 00:04:34.789
played for the Detroit Symphony.

00:04:34.789 --> 00:04:36.661
In those days, they
were the big orchestras

00:04:36.661 --> 00:04:40.296
who were on the radio,
that was The Ford Hour.

00:04:40.296 --> 00:04:43.840
- And so as your brother,
so how did that tie in too?

00:04:43.840 --> 00:04:46.339
- Well, I just wanted to
be like him if I could.

00:04:46.339 --> 00:04:47.877
You know, when you're five years apart,

00:04:47.877 --> 00:04:50.129
there's no contest of you competing.

00:04:50.129 --> 00:04:51.917
He can beat you up, he's smarter than you.

00:04:51.917 --> 00:04:53.681
(audience chuckles)
But he was so kind to me

00:04:53.681 --> 00:04:56.270
and encouraged me that I thought

00:04:56.270 --> 00:04:58.753
that if he had, he was so good at school

00:04:58.753 --> 00:05:00.372
that the family foot, he was gonna be

00:05:00.372 --> 00:05:05.199
the first doctor in our
Italian American family.

00:05:05.199 --> 00:05:06.828
So I thought I would be an eye doctor

00:05:06.828 --> 00:05:09.626
so I could work with lenses and prisms

00:05:09.626 --> 00:05:14.251
'cause I always loved prisms
and what light can do in a lab.

00:05:14.251 --> 00:05:17.033
So later in college, he flipped

00:05:17.033 --> 00:05:18.685
and became a philosophy major

00:05:18.685 --> 00:05:21.898
and told my father he
was gonna be a novelist,

00:05:21.898 --> 00:05:23.953
so then I said, "Well,
I'll be a playwright then."

00:05:23.953 --> 00:05:25.809
(audience laughs)

00:05:25.809 --> 00:05:28.137
So when I went, was ready in high school

00:05:28.137 --> 00:05:31.295
to consider college, I thought I would try

00:05:31.295 --> 00:05:34.545
to become a drama major and eventually,

00:05:35.879 --> 00:05:39.775
I entered school as a playwrighting major,

00:05:39.775 --> 00:05:43.805
but I of course worked in the
technical part of the theater,

00:05:43.805 --> 00:05:45.530
doing the lighting and stuff.

00:05:45.530 --> 00:05:48.063
One day when I was up on
a ladder hanging a light,

00:05:48.063 --> 00:05:50.781
I saw the teacher, who
was always the director,

00:05:50.781 --> 00:05:54.158
the shows were always
directed by faculty members,

00:05:54.158 --> 00:05:56.683
and I saw the teacher telling the kids,

00:05:56.683 --> 00:06:00.351
the actors, oh, you go here,
I thought I could do that.

00:06:00.351 --> 00:06:03.185
So in college, I started to direct plays

00:06:03.185 --> 00:06:06.185
and ultimately I was going to try to

00:06:07.216 --> 00:06:09.692
be a writer and director in the theater

00:06:09.692 --> 00:06:11.629
and in the theater in our country,

00:06:11.629 --> 00:06:13.829
the great theater graduate school,

00:06:13.829 --> 00:06:15.713
there are actually several great ones,

00:06:15.713 --> 00:06:18.435
but one of the great ones
is the Yale Drama School,

00:06:18.435 --> 00:06:20.091
which is a graduate school.

00:06:20.091 --> 00:06:23.882
So I was gonna be, go right
to the Yale Drama School

00:06:23.882 --> 00:06:28.639
and one afternoon, I was in
around the plaza of the college.

00:06:28.639 --> 00:06:30.953
I pretty much just hung
around the drama department.

00:06:30.953 --> 00:06:32.489
That was my life.

00:06:32.489 --> 00:06:34.340
I noticed a little theater that said

00:06:34.340 --> 00:06:38.423
today, 4:00 screening of
Sergei Eisenstein's film

00:06:39.369 --> 00:06:41.411
Ten Days That Shook the World.

00:06:41.411 --> 00:06:44.235
I'd never heard of Sergei Eisenstein

00:06:44.235 --> 00:06:46.979
and it was a silent film,
but I had nothing to do

00:06:46.979 --> 00:06:48.136
and I went in and there were about

00:06:48.136 --> 00:06:50.847
maybe six other people in the theater.

00:06:50.847 --> 00:06:54.937
No one was that interested
and it was truly silent

00:06:54.937 --> 00:06:57.241
and it lasted almost four hours

00:06:57.241 --> 00:06:59.824
and I had never seen a
film like that in my life,

00:06:59.824 --> 00:07:02.667
that the editing itself made up

00:07:02.667 --> 00:07:04.442
for the fact that there was no sound.

00:07:04.442 --> 00:07:06.847
When they shot machine
guns, you could hear them

00:07:06.847 --> 00:07:10.233
just by the way it was edited
because this Eisenstein,

00:07:10.233 --> 00:07:13.009
who was a film director in the '20s,

00:07:13.009 --> 00:07:17.176
invented and came up with new
ways of cutting film together,

00:07:18.248 --> 00:07:22.429
which is spoken of in his era as montage.

00:07:22.429 --> 00:07:25.711
The curious thing that
you could take a shot

00:07:25.711 --> 00:07:27.436
and cut it next to another shot

00:07:27.436 --> 00:07:30.031
and it means something different
than either of the shots

00:07:30.031 --> 00:07:32.465
is a kind of magic alchemy

00:07:32.465 --> 00:07:35.220
and I was just so impressed with that

00:07:35.220 --> 00:07:39.030
that I said, "I'm not going
to the Yale Drama School.

00:07:39.030 --> 00:07:41.253
"I wanna go to the UCLA Film School."

00:07:41.253 --> 00:07:43.569
I changed my whole life and went on

00:07:43.569 --> 00:07:46.660
to be a film student in America

00:07:46.660 --> 00:07:48.190
at a time when no film student

00:07:48.190 --> 00:07:51.081
had ever gotten to make a feature film.

00:07:51.081 --> 00:07:53.353
- So that raises the question.

00:07:53.353 --> 00:07:56.406
What was it about either the
mindset that you took to it

00:07:56.406 --> 00:07:59.083
or how you developed
yourself or even just fortune

00:07:59.083 --> 00:08:00.509
that put you in the right place

00:08:00.509 --> 00:08:03.011
that allowed you to do that
which you just described?

00:08:03.011 --> 00:08:06.222
A lot of students weren't
able to make a feature film.

00:08:06.222 --> 00:08:10.125
- Well, in college in
the drama department,

00:08:10.125 --> 00:08:12.854
I became very Machiavellian.

00:08:12.854 --> 00:08:14.900
Do any of you know what that word means?

00:08:14.900 --> 00:08:19.406
You all know that
Machiavelli was a minister.

00:08:19.406 --> 00:08:23.573
He was actually on the outs
with the prince in Florence

00:08:24.994 --> 00:08:28.111
and his name was Niccolo Machiavelli.

00:08:28.111 --> 00:08:30.560
So he wrote a little book about,

00:08:30.560 --> 00:08:34.239
a handbook for princes and
how to double cross people

00:08:34.239 --> 00:08:35.900
and how to do all those,

00:08:35.900 --> 00:08:37.899
what we now call Machiavellian things.

00:08:37.899 --> 00:08:39.262
There was more to him than that,

00:08:39.262 --> 00:08:41.316
but he's famous for that little book.

00:08:41.316 --> 00:08:43.827
That little book you can
read in about two hours.

00:08:43.827 --> 00:08:47.757
It's called The Prince
and it's all the rules of

00:08:47.757 --> 00:08:49.562
doing all those political things.

00:08:49.562 --> 00:08:52.107
I became very Machiavellian in college

00:08:52.107 --> 00:08:53.153
(audience laughs)

00:08:53.153 --> 00:08:57.021
because I wondered why
only the faculty members

00:08:57.021 --> 00:09:00.406
got to direct all the
plays and no students.

00:09:00.406 --> 00:09:02.381
So I did a little research
and I learned that

00:09:02.381 --> 00:09:05.531
the plays were paid for by the fees

00:09:05.531 --> 00:09:09.317
the students paid upfront for so-called

00:09:09.317 --> 00:09:11.772
co-curricular activities
or extracurricular.

00:09:11.772 --> 00:09:16.280
In other words, the
yearbook or the newspaper

00:09:16.280 --> 00:09:20.230
or the drama department, those
were all considered clubs

00:09:20.230 --> 00:09:24.084
and they were funded by student fees.

00:09:24.084 --> 00:09:27.159
There were two clubs
when I went to college

00:09:27.159 --> 00:09:30.231
at Hofstra College,
which is where the debate

00:09:30.231 --> 00:09:33.148
that Mrs. Clinton and Mr. Trump had

00:09:34.097 --> 00:09:35.672
two debates ago, was Hofstra College.

00:09:35.672 --> 00:09:38.129
That theater that they
were in, I know backwards.

00:09:38.129 --> 00:09:39.497
(Francis and audience laugh)

00:09:39.497 --> 00:09:43.244
So what I did is I became the president

00:09:43.244 --> 00:09:47.764
of both the musical comedy
club and the drama club,

00:09:47.764 --> 00:09:49.463
which were very different kinds of kids,

00:09:49.463 --> 00:09:54.461
but I became president of both
and I merged them together

00:09:54.461 --> 00:09:56.300
and then having merged them together,

00:09:56.300 --> 00:10:00.050
I made a rule that you
couldn't be in a show,

00:10:01.412 --> 00:10:03.721
to act in a musical or a play,

00:10:03.721 --> 00:10:06.541
unless you had not
missed the club meetings

00:10:06.541 --> 00:10:09.623
or at least you couldn't
have missed three in a row

00:10:09.623 --> 00:10:11.488
because no one ever went
to the club meetings.

00:10:11.488 --> 00:10:13.133
(audience laughs)

00:10:13.133 --> 00:10:14.447
Then but I did a good thing with it.

00:10:14.447 --> 00:10:16.598
We had the meetings, but I also invited

00:10:16.598 --> 00:10:19.791
everyone who wanted to to do
a little experimental workshop

00:10:19.791 --> 00:10:22.614
or a little one act play,
so the meetings were good,

00:10:22.614 --> 00:10:26.417
but during the meeting, I had
a vote and passed the rule

00:10:26.417 --> 00:10:29.132
that faculty members
could not direct shows

00:10:29.132 --> 00:10:31.248
that were funded by student money.

00:10:31.248 --> 00:10:32.274
(audience laughs)

00:10:32.274 --> 00:10:34.989
So suddenly all these drama
teachers who had come there

00:10:34.989 --> 00:10:37.872
so they could direct the
big show couldn't direct it.

00:10:37.872 --> 00:10:40.296
So I was the only student
who wanted to direct.

00:10:40.296 --> 00:10:42.844
(audience laughs)

00:10:42.844 --> 00:10:44.799
- Did you actually run for president

00:10:44.799 --> 00:10:47.250
of two separate clubs
and enact those rules

00:10:47.250 --> 00:10:50.519
with that in mind, that
I will get enough support

00:10:50.519 --> 00:10:51.855
by forcing people to go to these meetings

00:10:51.855 --> 00:10:55.456
and two clubs to allow
myself to direct the shows?

00:10:55.456 --> 00:10:57.367
- Well, it's a funny thing about power.

00:10:57.367 --> 00:10:58.834
(audience laughs)

00:10:58.834 --> 00:11:01.933
You don't necessarily know
that you're amassing it,

00:11:01.933 --> 00:11:03.334
but you sort of do.

00:11:03.334 --> 00:11:04.736
(audience laughs)

00:11:04.736 --> 00:11:06.241
But I was going in that direction

00:11:06.241 --> 00:11:07.589
and it worked very well for me

00:11:07.589 --> 00:11:11.117
because I got to do, not only
could I direct a production,

00:11:11.117 --> 00:11:15.009
but I used the strength
of having the finance,

00:11:15.009 --> 00:11:18.349
which was coming from the
club, we did ambitious shows.

00:11:18.349 --> 00:11:20.304
We did original musicals.

00:11:20.304 --> 00:11:22.997
We did a production of A
Streetcar Named Desire.

00:11:22.997 --> 00:11:24.526
We did all these wonderful things

00:11:24.526 --> 00:11:26.227
and many of the things were wonderful

00:11:26.227 --> 00:11:30.394
that brought life to the drama
department because of it.

00:11:31.649 --> 00:11:34.564
- How did you, so in college,
you get this great experience.

00:11:34.564 --> 00:11:37.339
You're directing it sounds
like big productions.

00:11:37.339 --> 00:11:41.756
How did that translate when you
first did your first movies?

00:11:41.756 --> 00:11:43.498
You did the screenplay for Patton.

00:11:43.498 --> 00:11:44.930
And you were quite young.
- Well, I went to the UCLA.

00:11:44.930 --> 00:11:47.682
In those days, there were two
or three big film schools.

00:11:47.682 --> 00:11:51.849
There was UCLA and USC and
in New York, there was NYU.

00:11:52.821 --> 00:11:56.855
To make it more clear for you,
Marty Scorsese went to NYU.

00:11:56.855 --> 00:12:00.943
George Lucas went to
USC and I went to UCLA.

00:12:00.943 --> 00:12:02.004
(audience chuckles)

00:12:02.004 --> 00:12:03.738
No one from any film school had

00:12:03.738 --> 00:12:06.649
ever made a feature movie, ever.

00:12:06.649 --> 00:12:10.984
So I sort of went to
UCLA with a big advantage

00:12:10.984 --> 00:12:14.038
'cause I had been a theater student

00:12:14.038 --> 00:12:17.653
and a theater student, one
of the fundamental things

00:12:17.653 --> 00:12:22.418
a theater student has to learn
is about writing and acting.

00:12:22.418 --> 00:12:25.785
Well, writing and acting
are the magical ingredients

00:12:25.785 --> 00:12:28.750
of any theater or cinema or performance.

00:12:28.750 --> 00:12:29.678
You could see a movie

00:12:29.678 --> 00:12:31.612
and it could have beautiful photography

00:12:31.612 --> 00:12:33.799
and it can have great art direction,

00:12:33.799 --> 00:12:37.056
but if it has terrible
acting and a dumb script,

00:12:37.056 --> 00:12:38.385
it's not gonna be successful.

00:12:38.385 --> 00:12:41.434
Yet, a film that has a wonderful script

00:12:41.434 --> 00:12:44.071
and wonderful acting that
has terrible photography

00:12:44.071 --> 00:12:48.065
and terrible art direction and
everything else can be a hit.

00:12:48.065 --> 00:12:51.787
So I always say that acting and writing

00:12:51.787 --> 00:12:55.954
is the water, is the oxygen
and hydrogen that make water,

00:12:57.176 --> 00:13:00.422
that if you focus on the
writing and the acting,

00:13:00.422 --> 00:13:03.394
of course you want the
music and the photography,

00:13:03.394 --> 00:13:05.396
everything to be beautiful,

00:13:05.396 --> 00:13:09.182
but those are really where
the magic I think happens.

00:13:09.182 --> 00:13:13.349
So having come from theater,
I knew a lot more about acting

00:13:14.315 --> 00:13:16.022
than any of the cinema students,

00:13:16.022 --> 00:13:18.110
who were much more into the camera.

00:13:18.110 --> 00:13:20.567
The great film director
Orson Welles once said

00:13:20.567 --> 00:13:21.830
that you can learn everything

00:13:21.830 --> 00:13:24.812
about how to make movies in a weekend,

00:13:24.812 --> 00:13:26.474
meaning the camera, the editing

00:13:26.474 --> 00:13:29.656
and more or less, of course
that's a little overdoing it.

00:13:29.656 --> 00:13:32.746
He, when he made his first
film, had a great photographer,

00:13:32.746 --> 00:13:34.933
but nonetheless, it's somewhat true.

00:13:34.933 --> 00:13:36.981
The camera and stuff is not the hard part.

00:13:36.981 --> 00:13:39.613
The hard part is the
writing and the acting.

00:13:39.613 --> 00:13:42.600
So having focused on that in theater,

00:13:42.600 --> 00:13:46.015
I had an advantage when I
went into the film school

00:13:46.015 --> 00:13:48.106
because there were philosophy students.

00:13:48.106 --> 00:13:51.523
Terrence Malick was a philosophy student.

00:13:52.784 --> 00:13:55.882
They were crazy to get
their hands on cameras

00:13:55.882 --> 00:13:59.395
and I had already worked with actors

00:13:59.395 --> 00:14:04.132
and also there's a sort of
prejudice against actors.

00:14:04.132 --> 00:14:05.034
I don't know if you know what I'm saying,

00:14:05.034 --> 00:14:07.050
but there's a sort of jock mentality

00:14:07.050 --> 00:14:09.024
about actors among the film crews.

00:14:09.024 --> 00:14:11.488
They think oh my god, they're such a,

00:14:11.488 --> 00:14:12.822
you know, what do they do after?

00:14:12.822 --> 00:14:15.340
Well, what an actor does is really hard

00:14:15.340 --> 00:14:18.259
because if you play a violin,

00:14:18.259 --> 00:14:20.503
not only do you have to be
able to play the violin,

00:14:20.503 --> 00:14:24.268
you've got the violin
between you and audience.

00:14:24.268 --> 00:14:27.723
The actor has to sort of
do what a violinist does,

00:14:27.723 --> 00:14:31.175
except his instrument
is himself or herself.

00:14:31.175 --> 00:14:34.065
So it's really terrifying to be an actor

00:14:34.065 --> 00:14:37.869
and at the same time fight
the self-consciousness

00:14:37.869 --> 00:14:39.829
that anyone would have.

00:14:39.829 --> 00:14:43.338
So I always approached movies and theater

00:14:43.338 --> 00:14:46.588
with tremendous respect for the actors.

00:14:47.854 --> 00:14:51.103
The actors, actresses today
like to be known as actors

00:14:51.103 --> 00:14:54.900
because it comes from the verb, to act.

00:14:54.900 --> 00:14:56.814
It's the one who acts.

00:14:56.814 --> 00:15:00.771
Not that you act a role,
which it indirectly means,

00:15:00.771 --> 00:15:04.291
but it's the actor means
the principle person

00:15:04.291 --> 00:15:05.928
making movement within the story.

00:15:05.928 --> 00:15:08.509
It could be a man or a
woman, could be an actor.

00:15:08.509 --> 00:15:11.568
Actress is sort of like
professoressa, you know?

00:15:11.568 --> 00:15:14.235
Lady professor, it's diminutive.

00:15:15.414 --> 00:15:17.138
So at any rate, I had this advantage of

00:15:17.138 --> 00:15:18.488
having been a drama student

00:15:18.488 --> 00:15:20.776
and also having been enough Machiavellian

00:15:20.776 --> 00:15:24.179
that I could conspire,
which is what you have to do

00:15:24.179 --> 00:15:27.120
to get a movie off the ground,
certainly in those days,

00:15:27.120 --> 00:15:30.524
to try to conspire to
put together a movie,

00:15:30.524 --> 00:15:32.051
which I did and I got to make.

00:15:32.051 --> 00:15:33.717
Because I was the first student

00:15:33.717 --> 00:15:36.953
to really make a feature film,

00:15:36.953 --> 00:15:41.290
some other students from USA
heard about this weird guy,

00:15:41.290 --> 00:15:43.606
notably George Lucas, who was about

00:15:43.606 --> 00:15:45.417
four years, five years younger than me.

00:15:45.417 --> 00:15:47.074
Four years younger than me.

00:15:47.074 --> 00:15:50.107
So he kind of came around,
this skinny kid with a beard

00:15:50.107 --> 00:15:53.550
when I was directing a
picture at Warner Brothers

00:15:53.550 --> 00:15:54.784
and this kid is watching me.

00:15:54.784 --> 00:15:58.043
Everyone on the show
is old and wore suits.

00:15:58.043 --> 00:15:59.427
He was this skinny kid with a beard

00:15:59.427 --> 00:16:01.157
and I looked at him looking at me

00:16:01.157 --> 00:16:02.570
and I said, "Well, what do you see?"

00:16:02.570 --> 00:16:04.127
