I mean, what's better
than learning how to think

00:24:40.044 --> 00:24:41.611
because you have to realize when

00:24:41.611 --> 00:24:45.044
these early people occupied the Earth,

00:24:45.044 --> 00:24:48.143
they didn't, no one was
there to teach them anything,

00:24:48.143 --> 00:24:50.776
so they had to decide for themselves

00:24:50.776 --> 00:24:53.794
and using the thought process
of, well, there's earth,

00:24:53.794 --> 00:24:56.424
there's fire, there's water, there's air.

00:24:56.424 --> 00:24:58.222
Maybe these are the basic elements.

00:24:58.222 --> 00:25:01.887
They just were using their
ability to think to uncover,

00:25:01.887 --> 00:25:04.609
so that's a wonderful
field, but in terms of film,

00:25:04.609 --> 00:25:06.235
what's interesting to me about film

00:25:06.235 --> 00:25:08.652
is that in the last 15 years,

00:25:09.850 --> 00:25:12.298
film which used to be a photochemical,

00:25:12.298 --> 00:25:14.578
in other words, we used
to have photographic film

00:25:14.578 --> 00:25:17.021
that you'd put in a mechanical device

00:25:17.021 --> 00:25:18.917
and would take a series of stills

00:25:18.917 --> 00:25:22.795
and then you had to send it
to the lab and develop it.

00:25:22.795 --> 00:25:27.371
In the last 15 years, all of
the elements of filmmaking

00:25:27.371 --> 00:25:29.698
have changed from photo, mechanical

00:25:29.698 --> 00:25:32.132
and mechanical to digital, electronic.

00:25:32.132 --> 00:25:35.503
So the editing machine
really is a computer now

00:25:35.503 --> 00:25:39.283
in which you compress the
images and put it in a computer

00:25:39.283 --> 00:25:42.145
and then you can cut them
together as you wish.

00:25:42.145 --> 00:25:45.812
The camera has become
so high in its quality

00:25:46.919 --> 00:25:50.910
that a digital camera is
sufficient to take the picture,

00:25:50.910 --> 00:25:54.498
which only 35 millimeter
film used to be able to take

00:25:54.498 --> 00:25:57.096
and the projector in
the theaters you go to

00:25:57.096 --> 00:25:58.294
when you go to the movie theaters,

00:25:58.294 --> 00:26:00.927
they're not loading up cans of film.

00:26:00.927 --> 00:26:03.652
They're also digital and there's possible

00:26:03.652 --> 00:26:05.120
to connect to them through satellite.

00:26:05.120 --> 00:26:09.633
So in the last 15 years,
everything about filmmaking

00:26:09.633 --> 00:26:14.118
or cinema has changed totally
to a different technology

00:26:14.118 --> 00:26:18.114
and my feeling is that
how could that happen

00:26:18.114 --> 00:26:19.913
without to some degree it changed

00:26:19.913 --> 00:26:22.564
the essence of what a movie is?

00:26:22.564 --> 00:26:25.639
Because now it's being
made so totally differently

00:26:25.639 --> 00:26:27.473
that perhaps there are new horizons

00:26:27.473 --> 00:26:30.492
that wouldn't have been
possible in the old days

00:26:30.492 --> 00:26:33.138
when it was really a piece
of photographic film.

00:26:33.138 --> 00:26:37.211
New things that we can do
that we couldn't do before

00:26:37.211 --> 00:26:39.196
and that's sort of personally what I'm,

00:26:39.196 --> 00:26:42.262
I'm experimenting with
something I call live cinema.

00:26:42.262 --> 00:26:43.288
What is live cinema?

00:26:43.288 --> 00:26:46.871
Live cinema means it's,
in my case, a story

00:26:49.274 --> 00:26:52.441
told like a movie, looks like a movie,

00:26:53.999 --> 00:26:57.419
except the actors are actually
doing it live in that moment.

00:26:57.419 --> 00:26:59.502
Now we all know that
they do live television,

00:26:59.502 --> 00:27:01.140
like some of you probably saw

00:27:01.140 --> 00:27:03.807
Peter Pan or The Sound of Music,

00:27:04.867 --> 00:27:07.089
but whenever you see a
live show on television

00:27:07.089 --> 00:27:10.530
or a soap opera or something,
it looks like television.

00:27:10.530 --> 00:27:12.433
It doesn't behave like a movie.

00:27:12.433 --> 00:27:14.703
Yet, when we see a movie on television,

00:27:14.703 --> 00:27:15.777
we know it's a movie.

00:27:15.777 --> 00:27:18.180
Even though it's coming on the same way,

00:27:18.180 --> 00:27:19.170
it looks like a movie.

00:27:19.170 --> 00:27:21.237
The way the story is told is different.

00:27:21.237 --> 00:27:25.552
The shots are telling the
action in a different way,

00:27:25.552 --> 00:27:27.572
so what I'm interested in is

00:27:27.572 --> 00:27:31.158
learning how it to be cinema still,

00:27:31.158 --> 00:27:33.186
that it looks and behaves like a movie.

00:27:33.186 --> 00:27:37.296
You wouldn't know that
it's even not a movie,

00:27:37.296 --> 00:27:40.073
except the actors are doing
it live in that moment.

00:27:40.073 --> 00:27:43.283
Then to do that, I did
two workshops recently,

00:27:43.283 --> 00:27:46.788
one at UCLA and one in
Oklahoma Community College

00:27:46.788 --> 00:27:50.288
where the school invited me
to work with their students

00:27:50.288 --> 00:27:54.736
and let me do my idea there,
as an experimental workshop,

00:27:54.736 --> 00:27:58.903
what we call a proof of concept,
to see if you could do it.

00:27:59.851 --> 00:28:02.167
I learned so much that
I wrote a little book

00:28:02.167 --> 00:28:03.570
that I'm just finishing called

00:28:03.570 --> 00:28:05.734
Live Cinema and Its Techniques

00:28:05.734 --> 00:28:09.539
and it's my hope personally
that I would get the opportunity

00:28:09.539 --> 00:28:12.731
before I do the final,
oh, I got to do this,

00:28:12.731 --> 00:28:15.231
I got to do that, to get to do

00:28:16.255 --> 00:28:19.838
some live cinema as
something I've written.

00:28:21.222 --> 00:28:23.479
I wanna remind you all that I used to be

00:28:23.479 --> 00:28:27.001
a drama counselor in a camp when I was 17,

00:28:27.001 --> 00:28:29.889
so I used to just, all summer,

00:28:29.889 --> 00:28:32.212
first week I'd do plays
with the six-year-olds,

00:28:32.212 --> 00:28:34.846
then I'd do plays with the
seven and eight-year-olds,

00:28:34.846 --> 00:28:36.597
then the nine and 10-year-olds,

00:28:36.597 --> 00:28:38.857
and then finally at the end of the summer,

00:28:38.857 --> 00:28:42.950
we'd bring the boys at
15 and the girls at 15

00:28:42.950 --> 00:28:45.689
from the nearby girls
camp and do a musical.

00:28:45.689 --> 00:28:47.178
Boy, was that an experience.

00:28:47.178 --> 00:28:49.468
(audience laughs)

00:28:49.468 --> 00:28:51.507
- Hi, Mr. Coppola, my name is Jia.

00:28:51.507 --> 00:28:54.049
I work on the sustainability
team here at Khan Academy.

00:28:54.049 --> 00:28:55.536
It's such an honor to have you here.

00:28:55.536 --> 00:28:57.119
I'm a huge fan of your films.

00:28:57.119 --> 00:29:00.420
I also love the films of
your daughter, Sofia Coppola.

00:29:00.420 --> 00:29:03.384
I wanted to ask what kind
of advice did you give her

00:29:03.384 --> 00:29:05.557
when she was starting out her film career

00:29:05.557 --> 00:29:07.870
and also how did you balance your role

00:29:07.870 --> 00:29:10.603
both as her father and as co-producer

00:29:10.603 --> 00:29:12.330
of some of her own films?

00:29:12.330 --> 00:29:13.163
Thank you.

00:29:13.163 --> 00:29:17.603
- Well, Sofia was always a
very precocious little kid.

00:29:17.603 --> 00:29:21.270
She was, even at age
six and seven, she was.

00:29:22.266 --> 00:29:23.718
I remember I once took her when she was,

00:29:23.718 --> 00:29:26.864
I mean, five or four, we all had to make,

00:29:26.864 --> 00:29:29.281
on Godfather II, we had to
go to Dominican Republic

00:29:29.281 --> 00:29:33.225
and we flew in this plane
and we got off in Miami

00:29:33.225 --> 00:29:36.638
and it was really hot and humid

00:29:36.638 --> 00:29:39.998
and I said to her, "Sofia,
how do you like Miami?"

00:29:39.998 --> 00:29:42.241
She said, "It's not my
ami, it's your ami."

00:29:42.241 --> 00:29:43.988
(audience laughs)

00:29:43.988 --> 00:29:47.405
So I knew I was in for a ride with Sofia,

00:29:48.413 --> 00:29:50.090
but it's interesting, she came to me

00:29:50.090 --> 00:29:53.056
when she was around 21, 22

00:29:53.056 --> 00:29:56.121
and she said, "Dad, I'm
interested in fashion

00:29:56.121 --> 00:29:59.030
"and I'm interested in
fashion photography."

00:29:59.030 --> 00:30:01.909
And she'd done some modeling
and designing clothes.

00:30:01.909 --> 00:30:03.726
"And I'm interested in writing stories,

00:30:03.726 --> 00:30:07.072
"but I really want to
be a painter and paint.

00:30:07.072 --> 00:30:09.271
"Am I just a dilettante?"

00:30:09.271 --> 00:30:12.485
I said to her, "You know,
parents always make the mistake

00:30:12.485 --> 00:30:15.177
"of wanting their kids
to focus in on something.

00:30:15.177 --> 00:30:16.823
"I'm telling you the opposite.

00:30:16.823 --> 00:30:17.891
"Don't focus.

00:30:17.891 --> 00:30:21.035
"Do everything you love
because if you learn

00:30:21.035 --> 00:30:23.768
"about everything you love, one day,

00:30:23.768 --> 00:30:25.583
"what you're meant to do in your life

00:30:25.583 --> 00:30:27.988
"will just come together for you

00:30:27.988 --> 00:30:29.569
"and it will be something that

00:30:29.569 --> 00:30:31.383
"makes use of all the different things.

00:30:31.383 --> 00:30:33.316
"Someday you'll find what you wanna do

00:30:33.316 --> 00:30:34.601
"and it will involve stories

00:30:34.601 --> 00:30:37.175
"and it will involve fashion
and all those things."

00:30:37.175 --> 00:30:39.007
And it turned out that a few years later,

00:30:39.007 --> 00:30:42.507
she made her short film at her high school

00:30:43.485 --> 00:30:46.326
and I could see that
she had a lot of talent.

00:30:46.326 --> 00:30:49.523
So I do think that parents often because,

00:30:49.523 --> 00:30:54.419
you know, we in the past, there
was a terrible depression,

00:30:54.419 --> 00:30:56.926
way before, in the '30s,

00:30:56.926 --> 00:30:59.613
but people were
traumatized that their kids

00:30:59.613 --> 00:31:03.176
needed to study something
they could make a living with

00:31:03.176 --> 00:31:07.718
and the best way to do
that is just don't special,

00:31:07.718 --> 00:31:10.355
I think that people may disagree,

00:31:10.355 --> 00:31:12.011
but don't specialize too young

00:31:12.011 --> 00:31:14.199
because being interested in one thing

00:31:14.199 --> 00:31:15.800
might stop you from thinking

00:31:15.800 --> 00:31:17.004
you could be interested in another thing.

00:31:17.004 --> 00:31:19.186
Be interested in everything you can be.

00:31:19.186 --> 00:31:21.297
Everything you love,
you should learn about

00:31:21.297 --> 00:31:23.738
because then one day, it
will all come together

00:31:23.738 --> 00:31:25.272
and be useful for whatever it is

00:31:25.272 --> 00:31:28.979
you choose you wanna do with your life.

00:31:28.979 --> 00:31:31.396
That was the case with Sofia.

00:31:34.845 --> 00:31:38.693
- Hello, I'm Sam from
KLS and I was wondering

00:31:38.693 --> 00:31:41.367
if you could travel back
in time to middle school,

00:31:41.367 --> 00:31:43.599
would you do anything differently?

00:31:43.599 --> 00:31:46.365
- What's middle school,
what grade is middle school?

00:31:46.365 --> 00:31:47.454
- [Sam] Sixth through eighth.

00:31:47.454 --> 00:31:49.734
- Well, sixth grade I was paralyzed

00:31:49.734 --> 00:31:53.028
in bed watching television.
(audience laughs)

00:31:53.028 --> 00:31:54.646
Watching television day and night

00:31:54.646 --> 00:31:57.536
and that was before the remote
control, so I was stuck.

00:31:57.536 --> 00:31:58.933
I couldn't walk to change it.

00:31:58.933 --> 00:32:00.038
(audience laughs)

00:32:00.038 --> 00:32:03.524
I was a prisoner of mid '50s television,

00:32:03.524 --> 00:32:06.342
but you know,
(audience laughs)

00:32:06.342 --> 00:32:10.509
my school, I went to 22 schools
