00:32:11.380 --> 00:32:14.695
so I was always, I felt like an outsider.

00:32:14.695 --> 00:32:16.695
I had no friends at all.

00:32:17.808 --> 00:32:19.685
You don't have time to make friends

00:32:19.685 --> 00:32:22.875
when you're there for six
months and I always did badly,

00:32:22.875 --> 00:32:25.116
so I was always in trouble with my father.

00:32:25.116 --> 00:32:27.813
I wish that I had the sense to say,

00:32:27.813 --> 00:32:31.723
when he was coming at me,
seeing my report card,

00:32:31.723 --> 00:32:34.609
with his belt folded in his
hand, I wish I had said,

00:32:34.609 --> 00:32:37.020
"But you take me out of
school every six months,

00:32:37.020 --> 00:32:39.951
"so how can I possibly get good marks?"

00:32:39.951 --> 00:32:43.725
So I was a sad lonely
kid through middle school

00:32:43.725 --> 00:32:46.346
and wanted to have friends

00:32:46.346 --> 00:32:47.993
and kept moving to different places

00:32:47.993 --> 00:32:50.135
and when you move as far away

00:32:50.135 --> 00:32:53.180
as from New York to California,
it's really different.

00:32:53.180 --> 00:32:56.461
In those days, L.A, Los Angeles

00:32:56.461 --> 00:32:57.662
was so different from New York.

00:32:57.662 --> 00:32:58.738
They didn't have baseball.

00:32:58.738 --> 00:33:01.778
They didn't have comic book stores.

00:33:01.778 --> 00:33:03.892
They didn't have White Castle hamburgers.

00:33:03.892 --> 00:33:05.379
(audience laughs)

00:33:05.379 --> 00:33:09.866
So I was just miserable at
your age, I hate to say,

00:33:09.866 --> 00:33:12.705
but Hemingway, Ernest
Hemingway, the writer,

00:33:12.705 --> 00:33:14.513
the famous American writer, said that

00:33:14.513 --> 00:33:15.469
if you wanna be a writer,

00:33:15.469 --> 00:33:17.170
you should have an unhappy childhood.

00:33:17.170 --> 00:33:20.869
So I had an unhappy childhood.
(audience laughs)

00:33:20.869 --> 00:33:23.733
- Hi, I'm Angelie from Khan Lab School

00:33:23.733 --> 00:33:25.741
and I was just wondering
what were some struggles

00:33:25.741 --> 00:33:29.074
that you had directing your first movie?

00:33:32.091 --> 00:33:36.099
- Well, my real first movie
was a little horror film

00:33:36.099 --> 00:33:39.432
that I made in Ireland when I was about,

00:33:40.279 --> 00:33:43.862
I mean, a feature film,
when I was about 21

00:33:44.912 --> 00:33:48.245
and you know, I guess what struck me was

00:33:49.661 --> 00:33:51.091
I always have been a person with

00:33:51.091 --> 00:33:53.868
a lot of good ideas or good imagination

00:33:53.868 --> 00:33:56.093
and I would always see all these things,

00:33:56.093 --> 00:33:57.402
but when you make a film,

00:33:57.402 --> 00:33:59.439
you have to take what's in your mind

00:33:59.439 --> 00:34:01.281
and what is your imagination

00:34:01.281 --> 00:34:04.896
and you have to find
practical ways to do it

00:34:04.896 --> 00:34:07.196
and it's not always as easy as you think,

00:34:07.196 --> 00:34:11.726
that it's kind of what they
say in car terminology,

00:34:11.726 --> 00:34:13.492
when the rubber meets the road.

00:34:13.492 --> 00:34:16.624
In other words, the world
of imagination and fantasy

00:34:16.624 --> 00:34:19.380
is wonderful because you have no limits.

00:34:19.380 --> 00:34:22.637
It's just as, you can just
cook something up in your mind,

00:34:22.637 --> 00:34:25.640
but then to translate that into a form

00:34:25.640 --> 00:34:27.849
that other people can see and enjoy

00:34:27.849 --> 00:34:29.808
involves a lot of practical stuff,

00:34:29.808 --> 00:34:33.975
of scheduling and budget and
the shot you had in mind,

00:34:35.540 --> 00:34:37.320
you can't really fit it in.

00:34:37.320 --> 00:34:38.750
It's not like you thought.

00:34:38.750 --> 00:34:42.689
So you have to learn as part
of the creative process,

00:34:42.689 --> 00:34:46.285
to learn to be inventive and flexible,

00:34:46.285 --> 00:34:48.444
to try to, there's two roads.

00:34:48.444 --> 00:34:51.789
There's what you imagined
and to what you can do

00:34:51.789 --> 00:34:53.801
and you have to be the one between those

00:34:53.801 --> 00:34:58.708
and use whatever cleverness
you can to get there.

00:34:58.708 --> 00:35:01.165
So when I made my first
film, I realized that

00:35:01.165 --> 00:35:04.251
the practical side was
really very important

00:35:04.251 --> 00:35:08.761
or you wouldn't get the
great ideas in the film.

00:35:08.761 --> 00:35:11.269
- So just to close out
and I think all of us

00:35:11.269 --> 00:35:12.370
would love to sit here all day

00:35:12.370 --> 00:35:15.413
and continue to, or all the whole week,

00:35:15.413 --> 00:35:19.246
(audience chuckles)
but just to finish off,

00:35:19.246 --> 00:35:20.917
there's some parallels
between what we're doing

00:35:20.917 --> 00:35:22.555
and things that you're interested in

00:35:22.555 --> 00:35:24.154
and that you have experience in,

00:35:24.154 --> 00:35:26.884
especially as, you know,
you just talked about film,

00:35:26.884 --> 00:35:29.127
going into a new era with the technology.

00:35:29.127 --> 00:35:30.683
Obviously, we're trying to do things

00:35:30.683 --> 00:35:32.096
along those lines in education,

00:35:32.096 --> 00:35:33.324
trying to reach a lot of folks.

00:35:33.324 --> 00:35:36.340
What advice in any form would
you have to everyone here,

00:35:36.340 --> 00:35:38.558
both the students and the
members of Khan Academy

00:35:38.558 --> 00:35:40.604
as we go off on our journey?

00:35:40.604 --> 00:35:43.587
- Well, all human beings
and all animals really

00:35:43.587 --> 00:35:46.554
seem to be good at play, we like to play.

00:35:46.554 --> 00:35:49.039
It's a natural thing we do

00:35:49.039 --> 00:35:53.420
and we have to realize
that work that we do

00:35:53.420 --> 00:35:56.159
later in life is really
a development of that.

00:35:56.159 --> 00:36:00.326
So I try to keep the work I
do as much like play as I can.

